<DOC><DOCNO> AP891224-0052 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-12-24-89 1826EST</FILEID><FIRST>u a AM-WeatherpageWeather 1stLd-Writethru a0806 12-24 0363</FIRST><SECOND>AM-Weatherpage Weather, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0806,0371</SECOND><HEAD>Winter Retains Icy Grip On Eastern States</HEAD><HEAD>Eds: SUBS 2nd graf to CORRECT number of cities with record lows to56, sted 57.</HEAD><BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE><TEXT>   The persistent cold wave gave Florida record lows Sunday, andstirred up a snowstorm that piled snow in 8-foot drifts in theCarolinas, but a slight warming trend moved onto the Plains   Record or record-tying lows were reported for 56 cities fromTexas to Florida and north to New England.   Temperatures dipped below zero as far south as Tennessee andfreezing temperatures were reported as far south as southernFlorida, where Miami cooled to a record 31 degrees.   The Florida Keys was the only place in the eastern half of thecountry without freezing temperatures from late Saturday intoSunday morning.   Sunday's official low for the Lower 48 states was 27 degreesbelow zero at Houlton, Maine, with unofficial lows of 33 below zeroreported in the West Virginia mountain valley communities of Gladyand Cheat Bridge.   Wind blew at 40 to 50 mph along the Outer Banks of NorthCarolina, causing considerable blowing and drifting snow andknocking down power lines. In Hyde County, on the coast of themainland, the wind created snow drifts up to 8 feet high.   Snowfall totals in eastern South Carolina ranged up to 14 inchesat Myrtle Beach, with 8 inches at Charleston.   Light snow dusted northern Florida, but much of the state gotice on roads and crops.   Light snow also dusted the southeastern corner of New England.   In the central part of the nation, temperatures rose rapidly.   The temperature hit 40 degrees at Chamberlain, S.D., andMinneapolis warmed into the 20s after nearly five straight daysbelow zero. Kansas City, Mo., had a December record of 16 belowzero Saturday, but highs in the 30s and 40s were predicted forMonday in the region.   Temperatures even remained above freezing overnight across partsof the northern Plains. Sunday's low of 33 at Dickinson, N.D., was66 degrees higher than the city's morning low on Friday.   Clouds and light snow accompanied the warmer weather from Kansasand Arkansas to Minnesota and Michigan.</TEXT></DOC>